# PowerShell Execution

## Objective
Simulate discovery-style reconnaissance using native PowerShell cmdlets instead of classic `cmd.exe` commands, to see how Wazuh handles PowerShell-based activity.

## Commands Run

| # | Command | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `Get-Process` | Lists every running process — attacker checks whether antivirus/security tools are active |
| 2 | `Get-Service` | Lists Windows services (Defender, SQL Server, backup software, RDP, etc.) |
| 3 | `Get-ChildItem C:\` | Lists files/folders on the C: drive to understand the file system |
| 4 | `Get-LocalUser` | Lists local user accounts, including admin/disabled accounts |

## Investigation — Wazuh Alert

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| agent.name | Windows11 |
| data.win.eventdata.commandLine | `cmd.exe /C echo.%UserProfile%` |
| data.win.eventdata.utcTime | 2026-07-04 19:52:11.400 |
| rule.description | Windows command prompt started by an abnormal process |
| rule.id | 92052 |
| rule.level | 4 |

## Takeaway
PowerShell-driven discovery still surfaces in Wazuh via process-spawn and command-line telemetry — reinforcing that Sysmon's process creation logging (Event ID 1) is what makes this kind of detection possible, regardless of which shell the attacker uses.
